      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Right Note</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Artist Celia Bowker letter on Bernard Holland's June 18 article describes how she was able, while listening to Mozart, to realize need to strike particular 'note' in painting (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am a visual artist whose work shares with music qualities which music explores superbly: pattern, repetition with variation, linear development, rhythm. A couple of years ago I was bogged down with murky painted passages. Listening to Mozart one day in my studio, I thought, ''A composer doesn't direct a pianist to play a note 'something like middle C.' She requires middle C or some other specific note.'' This helped me gather the courage to strike a particular ''note'' in my painting, as opposed to a mushy implication which never quite arrives or leaves.</p>
        <p>CELIA BOWKER  Seattle</p>
      </block>
